2026-04-16 12:22:12 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Module 3 input / output cable connections'] hypothesis_explanation='12 V is present at the output of control module 2, but both conductors at the output of control module 3 are at 0 V, even with all switches ON. That means the supply voltage is lost between module 2’s output and module 3’s output. Since modules 4–8 and the load also see 0 V, the first point in the chain where voltage disappears is around control module 3.\n\nWith all switches ON and with the indicator LEDs missing (so they cannot guide polarity), the most plausible fault is a wiring/configuration error on control module 3: the input/output cables of this module are mis‑connected (e.g., positive tied to negative, cables crossed, or both leads to the same rail), effectively pulling both outgoing lines to 0 V and preventing 12 V from propagating further.\n\nThus I hypothesize that the cable connections at control module 3 (either on its input side, its output side, or both) are faulty/misconfigured, and correcting/re‑wiring or replacing that cabling will restore 12 V to the rest of the chain and allow the lamp to operate when all switches are ON.'
